         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne:  ¶ Oct ¶ . 11  ¶ I have already written to you from the Murrumbidgee River about the extraordinary frequency of two of the dwarf salt-bushes from the Murrumbidgee to the Lachlan River, and ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">78.10.11c</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To the Gardeners' Chronicle</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found. The text given here is from 'Foreign correspondence', <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Gardeners' chronicle</seg>, 14 December 1878, p. 762 (B78.12.02).</p>
               </note>Melbourne: <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Oct</seg>. 11 </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">I have already written to you from the Murrumbidgee River about the extraordinary frequency of two of the dwarf salt-bushes from the Murrumbidgee to the Lachlan River, and beyond.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M to the <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Gardeners' chronicle</seg>, September 1878 (in this edition as 78-09-29a).</p>
               </note> The traveller may pass over plains unbroken as far as the eye reaches, and these almost exclusively occupied by <name key="Atriplex%20vesicaria">Atriplex vesicaria</name> and A. halimoides. Both bushes are nutritious to sheep, and will sustain also horses and cattle, especially in seasons of drought. I was told that the heat has exceptionally there culminated in 175° Fahr. in the sun, and 125° in the shade. This frightful heat, which drives birds into the buildings of the settlers, does not shrivel the <name key="Salsolaceae">Salsolaceae</name>, nor the foliage of the <name key="Eucalyptus%20rostrata">Eucalyptus rostrata</name> and some others; and there are besides numerous other plants which will bear this intense temperature, which far exceeds that given by Sachs<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Sachs (1874), pp. 697-8.</p>
               </note> as the limit of heat which a general vegetation will endure. I had an opportunity when on the Lachlan to trace a great many of the southern species so far northerly, whilst again a few tropical plants were found nearly as far south as the Murrumbidgee: for instance, Apophyllum anomalum, <name key="Goodenia%20cycloptera">Goodenia cycloptera</name> occurred in extraordinary abundance, <name key="Clianthus%20Dampieri">Clianthus Dampieri</name> grows here, not on sand, but on a firm loamy ground; it is a glorious object, visible at long distances. Some of the plains were quite white with <name key="Helipterum%20floribundum">Helipterum floribundum</name>, of which stock are very fond; other vast tracts have a violet tinge from the flowers of <name key="Swainsona%20procumbens">Swainsona procumbens</name>. I found on the Lachlan River also the curious <name key="Geococcus%20pusillus">Geococcus pusillus</name>, which, like <name key="Cardamine%20chenopodifolia">Cardamine chenopodifolia</name>, buries its pods in the soil for maturation. <name key="Senecio%20platylepis">Senecio platylepis</name>, previously known only from one spot, occurs on the Lachlan and Murrumbidgee Rivers millionfold, </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Ferd. von Mueller. </seg>
            </p>
